description: Borrowed from Latin obnūbilātus, perfect passive participle of obnūbilō (“cover with clouds or fog”), from ob- +‎ nūbilō (“be cloudy”), from nūbēs (“cloud”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *(s)newdʰ- (“to cover”).

adjectives.description: obnubilate (comparative more obnubilate, superlative most obnubilate)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Covered or darkened as with a cloud; overclouded; obscured.
examples: [B]ot sen I the to hir cure vassaill: // [To mak the r]efrane, my power laikis haill. // [For] in hir net thow art obnubilate: // [Gif] thow conuert, and tak my trew counsall // […]eng or lust thow suld neuer assaill. // […]waill hart fra hir to sequestrate, // […] time sa far as is fustrate: // […]oir repent, and thow sall ȝit preuaill.

description: Borrowed from Latin obnūbilō, as above.

verbs.description: obnubilate (third-person singular simple present obnubilates, present participle obnubilating, simple past and past participle obnubilated)
